{"id":6621,"date":"2016-09-18T22:43:29","date_gmt":"2016-09-18T22:43:29","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/?p=6621"},"modified":"2019-07-14T08:17:26","modified_gmt":"2019-07-14T08:17:26","slug":"scale-and-manage-virtual-machines","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/2016\/09\/18\/scale-and-manage-virtual-machines\/","title":{"rendered":"Scale and Manage Virtual Machines"},"content":{"rendered":"<p><a href=\"#Intro\">Introduction<\/a><\/p>\n<p><a href=\"#Part 1\">Part 1: What are Virtual Machine Scale Sets<\/a><\/p>\n<p><a href=\"#Part 2\">Part 2: Building a Scale Set<\/a><\/p>\n<p><a href=\"#Con\">Conclusion<\/a><\/p>\n<hr \/>\n<h3 id=\"Intro\">Introduction<\/h3>\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/2015\/09\/21\/how-to-upload-a-virtual-machine-to-the-cloud-for-microsoft-azure\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><strong>Virtual Machines<\/strong><\/a> can be scaled and managed using <strong>scale sets<\/strong>. <strong>Scale sets<\/strong> are essentially a way for you to manage a set of <strong>Virtual Machines<\/strong> as a single unit. Before <strong>scale sets<\/strong>, when you wanted to have a bunch of <strong>virtual machines,<\/strong> you would spin them up manually or through some script or something and then you would have to manage them yourself but now, <strong>scale sets<\/strong> have made it very easy to manage hundreds of <strong>virtual machines<\/strong> at a time. You can also visit<strong> Microsoft Azure website<\/strong> to learn more about <strong><a href=\"https:\/\/azure.microsoft.com\/en-us\/documentation\/articles\/virtual-machine-scale-sets-overview\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Virtual Machine Scale Sets<\/a> <\/strong>and <strong><a href=\"https:\/\/azure.microsoft.com\/en-us\/documentation\/articles\/virtual-machine-scale-sets-windows-create\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">How to Create a Windows Virtual Machine Scale Set using Azure PowerShell<\/a>.<\/strong><\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p class=\"blue\"><span class=\"ion-tip\">Tip<\/span>If you would like to learn more about my personal experience of the Migration Team Foundation Server to Visual Studio Team Services using Database Import Service or TFS Migrator. The TFS Database Import Service, also known shorthand as the Import Service, provides a high fidelity way to migrate collection databases from TFS to VSTS- have a look at this post &#8211; have a look at the <a href=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/2018\/04\/09\/migrating-team-foundation-server-to-visual-studio-team-services-using-database-import-service-tfs-migrator\/\"><strong>this post<\/strong><\/a><\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p class=\"gray\"><span class=\"ion-video\">Video<\/span> You can see <strong><a href=\"https:\/\/www.youtube.com\/watch?v=OROfBriR_YU\">this video<\/a><\/strong>, if you would like to find more information about how to develop your first project for Microsoft Dynamics 365 CRM Project. Understand the main components, structure and process of the development for Microsoft Dynamics 365 CRM. Get the full picture of the development cycle and learn how to create a new CRM solution. In this video, you are going to see how to develop a Dynamic CRM plugin and deploy it to CRM solution using xrmtoolkit, and how to develop web resources including an HTML page and embed it inside CRM.<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<h3 id=\"Part 1\">Part 1: What are Virtual Machine Scale Sets<\/h3>\n<p><strong>Virtual Machine Scale Sets<\/strong> are a way to deploy and manage a set of identical <strong>Virtual Machines<\/strong>. So with <strong>Azure infrastructure service<\/strong> if you want fifty <strong>virtual machines<\/strong> you normally have to think about networking, storage, extensions, underlying infrastructure and how you configure these <strong>virtual machines<\/strong> &#8211; <strong>virtual machine scale sets<\/strong> give you a way to create many <strong>virtual machines<\/strong> and then just configure the properties and manage them as a set.<\/p>\n<p><strong>Scale sets<\/strong> also integrate with <strong>Azure Autoscale<\/strong> &#8211; this means you can dynamically grow and shrink the pool of <strong>virtual machines<\/strong>.<strong>\u00a0Scale sets<\/strong> also integrate with <strong>Azure Load Balancer.<\/strong><\/p>\n<p>Another way to look at<strong> scale sets<\/strong> is an <strong>Azure Compute resource<\/strong> as part of <strong>Azure Resource Manager<\/strong>. <strong>Scale sets<\/strong> are scalable computer layer for hyperscale apps &#8211; what that means is if you have a large scale applications with multiple components that uses Microsoft services and has different areas that you can configure, you can use <strong>scale sets<\/strong> to be a generalized computer layer. In a similar way <strong>scale sets<\/strong> can be used as an infrastructure for <strong>Platform as a Service (PaaS)<\/strong>.<\/p>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-6548\" title=\"1 what-are-virtual-machine-scale-sets\" src=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/09\/What-are-Virtual-Machine-Scale-Sets-1.jpg\" alt=\"1 what-are-virtual-machine-scale-sets\" width=\"763\" height=\"398\" srcset=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/09\/What-are-Virtual-Machine-Scale-Sets-1.jpg 1337w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/09\/What-are-Virtual-Machine-Scale-Sets-1-300x157.jpg 300w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/09\/What-are-Virtual-Machine-Scale-Sets-1-768x401.jpg 768w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/09\/What-are-Virtual-Machine-Scale-Sets-1-1024x535.jpg 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 763px) 100vw, 763px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p class=\"blue\"><span class=\"ion-tip\">Tip<\/span>If, after adding a new user to <a href=\"https:\/\/dynamics.microsoft.com\/en-gb\/\">Dynamics 365<\/a>, you get the following error: <em>You do not have permissions to see this view. Contact a system administrator crm, <\/em>, &#8211; have a look at the <a href=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/2018\/03\/07\/fix-you-do-not-have-permissions-to-see-this-view-contact-a-system-administrator-crm\/\"><strong>this post<\/strong><\/a><\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p class=\"green\"><span class=\"ion-info\">More Info<\/span>If you would like to learn more about using the <a href=\"https:\/\/docs.microsoft.com\/en-us\/vsts\/build-release\/concepts\/definitions\/build\/variables?tabs=batch\">Build Variables<\/a> in <a href=\"https:\/\/www.visualstudio.com\/team-services\/\">VSTS<\/a> and Release Management, &#8211; have a look at the following post: <a href=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/2018\/03\/11\/vsts-build-variables-and-echo\/\">VSTS Build variables and Echo<\/a>. The post describes how to see the output at any point of time. While automating a process, through setting variables and displaying them during the build.<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<h3 id=\"Part 2\">Part 2: Building a Scale Set<\/h3>\n<p>1. Go to <strong><a href=\"https:\/\/github.com\/azure\/azure-quickstart-templates\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Azure Quickstart templates GitHub<\/a>\u00a0<\/strong>and select any template. This is a great place to find examples of how to use <strong>Virtual Machine Scale Sets<\/strong>.<\/p>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-6549\" title=\"2-1 Azure-quickstart-templates-GitHub\" src=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/09\/Azure-Quickstart-Templates-Github.jpg\" alt=\"2-1 Azure-quickstart-templates-GitHub\" width=\"763\" height=\"406\" srcset=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/09\/Azure-Quickstart-Templates-Github.jpg 1367w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/09\/Azure-Quickstart-Templates-Github-300x160.jpg 300w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/09\/Azure-Quickstart-Templates-Github-768x408.jpg 768w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/09\/Azure-Quickstart-Templates-Github-1024x545.jpg 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 763px) 100vw, 763px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>2. Click on <strong>Deploy to Azure<\/strong>. This will take you to <strong>Azure Portal<\/strong>.<\/p>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-6550\" title=\"2-2 Deployment-of-VM-scale-set\" src=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/09\/Deployment-of-VM-Scale-Set.jpg\" alt=\"2-2 Deployment-of-VM-scale-set\" width=\"763\" height=\"404\" srcset=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/09\/Deployment-of-VM-Scale-Set.jpg 1372w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/09\/Deployment-of-VM-Scale-Set-300x159.jpg 300w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/09\/Deployment-of-VM-Scale-Set-768x406.jpg 768w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/09\/Deployment-of-VM-Scale-Set-1024x542.jpg 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 763px) 100vw, 763px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>3. You will see <strong>Custom Deployment Section<\/strong>. Click on <strong>Edit Parameters<\/strong>.<\/p>\n<p>4.\u00a0Fill out the <strong>parameters<\/strong> as per your needs.<\/p>\n<p>5. Click on <strong>OK<\/strong>.<\/p>\n<p>6.\u00a0Create a <strong>new Resource group<\/strong>.<\/p>\n<p>7.\u00a0Type the <strong>name for your Resource group<\/strong>.<\/p>\n<p>8.\u00a0Click on <strong>Create<\/strong>.<\/p>\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/2016\/09\/18\/scale-and-manage-virtual-machines\/2-3-scale-set-custom-deployment\/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-6622\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-6622\" title=\"2-3-scale-set-custom-deployment\" src=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2016\/09\/2-3-Scale-Set-Custom-Deployment.jpg\" alt=\"2-3-scale-set-custom-deployment\" width=\"763\" height=\"363\" srcset=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/u